caption: They blackened ribs never disappoint. Great corner location in Jackson Square with good food
Great place to try out. The location is right next to Jackson Square. The staff was very nice!

Nice location in jackson square. Friendly staff. The crab cakes eggs benedict was tasty. The only downside was my eggs were not poached. However the crab cakes were flavorful and the mimosa was nice. Depending on the time of day, there will be a line. It's a nice spot.
Excellent place! Indeed swing by there

Great location and staff but food was disappointing. I had the combination of gumbo, jambalaya, and crawfish pie. Gumbo and jambalaya were too salty. Wife had jambalaya and agreed it was too salty. I liked the crawfish pie. Daughter had creole shrimp and really liked it. It was a good choice for her since it was mild in spiciness.
We enjoyed Cafe Pontalba's Jambalaya and a combination plate including gumbo, red beans, and rice. The wait person was friendly and efficient.
Ate the crawfish poboy for lunch and had a couple hurricanes. Our server was nice and the bathrooms were clean.

Stopped here for breakfast and the staff was so friendly and welcoming. I got Eggs Benedict over potatoes.  Loved the creole spice on the potatoes. Tasted like Tony Chachere’s which is my favvvvorite! I wanted a drink but wasn’t sure what I wanted and the waiter recommended a brandy milk punch and it hit the spot perfectly!

We had breakfast at this restaurant. The coffee was weak and the food was half from frozen potatoes and the other half had spoiled meat. We informed the waiter payed our bill and left. We live a block away and will not return.
Do not try the bloody Mary. Tastes like Tony's and watered down tomato juice. Food was good.
Awesome!!

Meh.

Everything was simply the greatest food I have ever eaten. The service was as good as the food. I can't wait to eat here again.
Great prices and amazing food. You can people watch Jackson Square folks. Ask for Luke, awesome waiter.

Very relaxed atmosphere.. The staff is very friendly and its right in the middle of the action.. Step outside of the doors and regardless of what direction you walk, you will find NOLA charm, history, culture and excitement! Enjoy!
Solid food choice

The French Toast was good, but the cajun potatoes were a little disappointing, the flavor is good, but they are not crisp.  The hot cocoa drink was delicious and hit the spot to warm up with.  Covid: Must put name/number and the number of members of your party for contract tracing.  Tables are spaced out fairly well.
Visited last week. My pasta was outstanding and the service was even better! Awesome views and live music from the square as well. I'd visit again.
2 for 2!! 2nd time in three weeks we ate here. Mickey highly recommended the Mardi Gras pasta! Blend of chicken, shrimp, and sausage. Excellent! Clean restrooms, too!

Gumbo was really good. Jambalaya was too dry. The crab cake was also too dry. Should have added more crawfish sauce on top. Shrimp and grits and no flavor. Blackened fish was flavorful and perfectly cooked.
Love it!

Kinda basic. It’s a great location. The gentleman who served us was wonderful. It’s pretty to eat an be able to look out. Honestly I picked this place cause of the location an the views. But I should have read about the food. I would say the plates were decent sized portions (it’s a cafe not a restaurant). Price was decent too. My issue was the food. They say Cajun but it looks like all they did was sprinkle Cajun powder on it an bam called it that. The food could have been better. The crab was black which I’m pretty sure crab is white. An what ever meat was on my breakfast had to have been frozen prior. Overall it’s a nice place to get a small snack an a drink but I wouldn’t particularly eat eat here.

Best Hamburger I ever had Since I was the only meat eater in my group I went in alone.  The staff was so friendly I asked for the Cajun Burger it blew my mind afterwards the waiter came and asked how was everything I told him.  This is the best Hamburger I ever had.  He told me he was excited that I asked for it and smile at me.  Thank you for a wonderful experience.
Best alligator we've had so far, we got half blackened and half fried. Excellent!

We were in a hurry, so we called ahead. Luke answered the phone, placed our order, and had it packed for pickup just before we arrived. Brought it back home for last minute out of town guests. Great food and service! Bravo, Luke!!
Great outdoor seating, perfect spot for a po-boy or crab cakes and people watching.
Awesome food!
Delicious food and great service
Excellent service and food!  friendly people. They even let us sit with our dog.
Great food, great atmosphere, great drinks...right in the square! Our server was Mike, great guy! Def. Recommend.
Really good food!
Because of this place, crawfish pie is my new favorite dish. Amazing cocktails as well. Bloody mary with a nice kick and pickled green beans! Other drink was sweet and fruity.
Breakfast was excellent for a large group on Boxing Day. We had some extreme dietary requirements and they managed it all without a problem.
Literally the beat BBQ shrimp you'll ever order in your life. Period.
Pleasant service and great drinks. Get the Voodoo Juice. I love the voodoo that you do so well...

The service was great, and so was the location and atmosphere. Had a shrimp po-boy. It was pretty good. I liked their signature sauce even though it was spicy. It wasn't as fantastic as I always imagined po-boys to be, but maybe it was an off day
Awesome brunch

Something about N.O. I love the architecture of the buildings. If only the walls could talk. But anyway this just looked like a really cool spot to grab a bite to eat. And it sure was. Red beans and rice were so good, flavorful, filling, I almost slapped someone at the table next to me, but thank God for social distancing I couldn't reach! The wife had the Crawfish combination plate, she said everything was good, she loved the flavor. My first born had a crawfish po boy, the size of his head and loved it. My daughter ordered what we thought would be fish sticks but really fresh fish filets, flaky falling apart fresh fish for kids!!!! Staff was great. Go enjoy the vibe, enjoy the food, take it all in. Awesome experience.

I had a decent time.  The food was spicy the way I like it.  the calamari was good.  The beans were spicy.  I liked the blackened redfish with the crafiah topping.  I purchased the blackened alligator pictured.  I was full .  The restaurant has decent space and good service.  I do recommend
They had the BEST seafood  platter that I have ever eaten! Lots of history at this restaurant.....

I have been trying to get back to this place for 4 years and I finally did!!! I had a blackened shrimp caesar salad 4 years ago that had so much shrimp I could barely see the salad.  It was seriously one of the most delicious meals I had in New Orleans and could not stop thinking about it.  I actually had to delay my departure to eat there this time because they are only open Thursday-Sunday but it was so worth it!!!! I called ahead, yes, crazy I know, but I had to be certain I could get this salad again.  They did not disappoint!!!  They went above and beyond for me and I especially have to thank Darrin and Mickey.  First of all the location is killer and this day they had the doors all open street side which feels very much like a European cafe.  The blackened shrimp caesar salad was sensational with more shrimp than I could count, perfectly dressed, with large homemade garlic croutons.  I was in heaven!!!  And since it was literally my last time before leaving New Orleans, I had to try the key lime pie, which was delicious and surprising.  It tasted almost like an ice cream cheesecake, refreshing and cold. So yummy!!!  Without a doubt, there is much great food in New Orleans, but this charming little cafe is truly a hidden gem and shouldn't be missed!

It's a bit pricey, but location is everything in this business and they definitely have a great location. An amazing staff, very attentive, and the food was fantastic. Definitely recommend the blackened alligator Cesar salad. The dining room is very open with a stunning appearance. Very clean and inviting.
Great atmosphere right by the Square.  Reasonably priced and the food was delicious!
The staff was wonderful, and the food was delicious! I just ate there two days ago and I'm already craving that red beans and rice again.
Great food, interesting location.
Surprisingly good prices for being in the heart of the quarter. Slammed most weekends but usually not too busy during the week. Fish po' boy is a must have.
Great food, server was awesome. Key lime pie was excellent. Prefect views of St. Louis Cathedral and Jackson Square.
Excellent food! We had shrimp two different dishes. Customer service friendly and efficient. Atmosphere was relaxing and clean!!
Very American breakfast! Filled us up. Joe had us covered remind me of Justin Williams.
The Rajin Cajun Pasta was delicious.  It had just the right amount heat but not over powering for your taste buds.  Service was great.  We are in New Orleans often and will definitely return.
Gumbo is delish, great place for a beer.  I've come for lunch and dinner, never disappoints.
Food is delicious! Service is great! Bloody Mary’s to top off an all around awesome experience!!
Goodfood
Food was wonderful service was outstanding!

Right on Jackson Square. This place would be a go to place even if the food was marginal. Location, location, location. Luckily with it a worthy establishment and worthy of the crowd it attracts.  For dinner I had the Cajun Combination. I knew it would be my only stop here so took the opportunity to try a little variety as you might think to. Here’s what I found. The gumbo was very good, worthy of a whole bowl. The jambalaya was good but nothing too special. It was more rice than meat but it paired well with the other mound on the plate, the crawfish etouffee. I found the etouffee to be quite tasty and to have a decent amount of meat. The sauce itself was very nice. It also came with crawfish pie which are like samosas but with a crawfish mix inside the dough. I found the dough to be a bit overwhelming and thick. It was doughy and was off balance to the mixture inside. It could gave been a bid night for the dough but as they were I would not recommend them, and so probably not the combination either.  This is a bustling restaurant the atmosphere is fun in its own way and you may have to wait. They do seem to have a system to move people through but I never felt rushed. I would not hesitate to go back here again, but, as I said, I would not get the combination. Something  like the Gumbo and a full entree comes to mind.
Good cafe excellent gumbo service hit or miss!
Waiter was amazing. (Older gentleman with beard and sunglasses) Food was great as well, had chicken breast and potatoes/fries. Overall great experience.

Terrible service. I sincerely regret wasting time and money here. Waited nearly 30 minutes to be greeted by a server and finally get drink orders. Waited longer to finally order food and the food was bland.
I was excited to try some nice Cajun food but was disappointed. Food was nowhere close to what we had in some of the other local restaurants. New Orleans food is so delicious , but NOT this place.

My husband and I were having our honeymoon in NOLA, and we were so glad to have stopped in to Cafe Pontalba! We were able to choose our own table, which was right on the edge of the restaurant, so we had an amazing outdoor/indoor experience. We had a perfect view of Jackson Square. The food was delicious. I got the crawfish Caesar salad, and my husband gor a burger. I also got the Mardi Gras Hurricane. We were both quite pleased with the quality of the food & drinks. The place shined even brighter because of the server. I’m sad to have not gotten his name, but he was the only server in the place and blew us away with his attentiveness and courteousness. Even after we paid for our meal, he offered to refill our waters so that we could remain at our table to relax and enjoy ourselves. My husband and I couldn’t stop talking about how much we appreciated his amazing service. If you want a reasonably priced place with good food, great atmosphere, and excellent service, we recommend Cafe Pontalba!

Café Pontalba is beautifully situated on a lovely corner just across from Jackson Square. They offer floor to ceiling windows that open to provide wonderful views of Jackson Square, the Cabildo, Saint Louis Cathedral and all of the street performers and wandering crowds to be found there. This is a great place for people watching. We went in at 12:30 p.m. one afternoon, drawn in by the breakfast sign outside, only to find that they stop serving breakfast at noon (wish they had taken in their sign). Our server, nice enough without being especially friendly, was patient with our mistake when we needed more time to look at the lunch menu. We had the Cajun Combination and the Creole Combination and found them to be typical Louisiana fare but nothing particularly special. We were there on a rainy, spring afternoon and found the inside of Café Pontalba to be surprisingly dark. No additional lighting was turned on while we were there to combat the gloominess of the weather. The view of Café Pontalba from the outside gives an impression of a lively place for a good meal right on Jackson Square. No real complaints here, however, I found this to be a very mediocre lunch experience as compared to what I expected.

They have live entertainment right outside as well as local artists displaying their artwork. However, the food.... the food. I had the shrimp and grits. Very basic. The grits needed a LOT of seasoning. The food did its job by sustaining me but my taste buds didn’t do a happy dance. My nephew had the crawfish omelette and he said it was really really good. My brother in law had the eggs benedict and  potatoes and he said they both were average. The Bloody Mary and mimosas were good. The pickled green beans in the Bloody Mary was sooooo good!
Had the BBQ Shrimp. Was not very good. Shrimp small and hard to peel and the sauce was very oily.

A must-visit place in New Orleans! A Sunday morning Bloody Mary and steak while gazing at St. Peter's Cathedral, Jackson Square & the balconys overlooking the street is always perfect!

We ate here multiple times and always had great food and service. Possibilities are endless.

Probably the surliest waitress in New Orleans. Arrived 11.30 and apparently too early for the lunch menu. Nothing on the breakfast menu appealed and so I suggested a coffee and I would wait until 12. The response was "well you can't sit at the table if you not eating. You can go sit at the bar". And that would be fair enough if the place was not half empty. And it has to be said that most other places were pretty full. Unsurprised. But maybe Must be bad day because a bit later a smile and a top of coffee and a lunch menu. Let's see how this goes. We were in New Orleans for Mardi Gras exploring the city.  We wondered through Bourbon street and into the French Quarters and stopped here for lunch because there was no wait time.  It was around 3 pm on a very busy Saturday afternoon.  The place was pretty busy but we were seated right away and our drink order was taken.  Our entire table ordered po-boys from here with a side of Cajun potatoes.  The wait for the food was not to long considering how busy the restaurant was.  The po-boys were typical po-boys: not too great but also not too bad.  The potatoes however were very tasty. I would not come here again for a po-boy and you are probably better off trying some place else for that. Perhaps the rest of their menu is better.  In short, the service was great but the food was nothing exceptional.
Excellent food and service.
I had the shrimp and grits,  and Marsha had crab cakes benedict and they were fabulous.    They also have beer, for the morning drinker.
Clean place, quick service, good food. Prices range from $10-20 per meal. Great jambalaya! We can during Mardi Gras at lunch time and were seated within 15 minutes.

Great location.  Average food.  Slow service. It's right across the street from Jackson Square.  Nice view. I was trying to decide if I wanted to get the bbq shrimp or the fried shrimp.  Boyfriend suggested that I ask for a taste of the bbq sauce.  He's so smart.  I did and it was good, average sauce, so I decided on the bbq shrimp.  Then the waitress told me they didn't use the bbq sauce on the bbq shrimp.  Silly me.  She went on to describe what they did use.  It didn't sound appetizing, so I got the fried shrimp.  It was pretty good.  The breading was buttery and crisp.  The shrimp was fresh.  But it was nothing special.  The fries were awful.  A little undercooked and tasteless.  Boyfriend said his Cajun Combo was "good."  It was all fine, but one doesn't come to N'arlins for fine. The service was slow, despite the lack of customers.  Everything took a little longer than it should have, from being seated to getting our water to getting a sample of the bbq sauce that was not on the bbq shrimp to getting the bill. And there's no air conditioning.  Which is partly on me.  Who visits Louisiana in August? There was nothing horrible.  But one goes to the French Quarter for amazing food and this wasn't it.
Fantastic food especially the Étouffée.  Will definitely be back.
Right on Jackson Square and is a very easy and accessible spot for food any time of the day. Very friendly and engaging staff, and great food!
Delicious french toast!

I visited this restaurant on January 6, 2019 from 18:00 to 19:00. Despite the waiting crowds for the parade, it was not full. Here are the issues I had:  1) It took 15 minutes to take my order. 2) Waitress had to come back after each order to ask me what I ordered! 3) There was no Wifi! This in the French Quarter where most establishments have it! 4) The key lime pie tasted like an ice cream sandwich with cream on top! 5) The jambalaya was dry and the meat especially the chicken overcooked! 6) The bathroom was dirty! 7) The coffee was tepid when brought to me and I had to order a new one! 8) There was no ice in the drink! I did not leave a tip because this restaurant despite its rave reviews was simply mediocre. I honestly got better service and value for my money in the little restaurant down the road from the Whitley Plantation!

Pro: good food, awesome location. We got an open window seat which made it feel very European. Food tasted good, and for how busy everywhere else was, we had no wait. Con: a little pricey ($10/kids meals and $14+ for adults for the simple meals). Small portion sizes.
Drinks were good and affordable.  Waitress was lovely and helpful.  She did everything we asked. Food was ok.  Red beans and rice were great.
The bathroom is filled with poop on the floor and walls and the food was awful. WOULD NOT RECOMMEND or ever go back.

Very slow to be seated. Table was dirty, the drink menus were actually wet. Po-boy ham sandwich had a very big roll with a very small single slice of what looked like lunch meat. Very expensive (almost $90 for a burger, a po-boy sandwich and pasta with a small appetizer.). Water was served in plastic cups. Tourist trap, go elsewhere.
Absolutely the worst restaurant I have ever been to. Food was not hot, service was slow, flavor was poor. Enough said.

Horrible service. Rude, major attitude, unprofessional. We were a large party (10) and requested to sit in small groups to manage the bill. The host (manager?) kept saying it would be no problem to put us together, even though we'd already sat down separately, so we finally just agreed. Now I see why. If we're together, they can force us to pay an 18% tip to the rudest waitress I've ever had. Be aware....refills on soft drinks are NOT free. The food was mediocre at best. No wonder there was no line to get in. Just go elsewhere.
